<TITLE> Shahabuddin reveals not much about 10-truck arms haul </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Chittagong, May 5 (bdnews24.com)Police have started quizzing a former NSI director, retired wing commander Shahabuddin, in the widely discussed Chittagong 10 truckloads of arms haul case, but he is not revealing much. Shahabuddin was interrogated in the office of Criminal Investigation Department in Chittagong from Tuesday morning until evening. The investigation officer of the case, CID senior assistant police superintendent Moniruzzaman Chowdhury said Shahabuddin did not give any important information on the first day of his three-day remand in custody. Moniruzzaman said the Shahabuddin, former NSI director, security, did not answer most of the questions. The official did not enlarge on the details for the sake of investigation. Another CID officer said on the condition of anonymity that Shahabuddin was being questioned about four matters: who directed him to order NSI field officer Akbar Hossain Khan to hire the trucks, his relationship with India's separatist ULFA leader Paresh Barua, and the role of the home minister in the arms haul. Shahabuddin was produced before Chittagong Metropolitan Magistrate's Court Monday. Khan said Saturday that he had hired trucks for carrying the arms under Shahabuddin's orders. Uddin was arrested at his Green Road house that night. The huge arms, ammunition and explosives were unloaded at the Chittagong Urea Fertiliser Limited jetty on the night of April 1, 2004. bdnews
